Energy CS Charles Keter (pictured) has warned candidates not to make illegal power connections to woo voters.He said on Tuesday some aspirants with deep pockets have been connecting power and street lights in their regions.Keter said this is illegal and will be punished. He spoke in Gatuanyaga, Thika East, where he launched the Last Mile project and security lights.Keter said KPLC is the only company mandated to instal electricity and street lights. He said the ministry will punish individuals illegally connecting power. &ldquo;If they have a lot of money, they can give it to the government and then the work will be done by the right people,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;Some aspirants are also installing electricity for residents . This is illegal and endangers lives because because nonexperts are used,&rdquo; Keter said.